# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boost-controller
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:boost-controller/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:boost-controller/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:boost-controller/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:boost-controller/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:boost-controller/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] In distributed systems in particular event-driven architecture, back pressure is a technique to regulate flow of data, ensuring that components do not become overwhelmed.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] In a piston-ported two-stroke engine, however, the situation is more complicated, due to the need to prevent unburned fuel/air mixture from passing right through the cylinders into the exhaust.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] During the exhaust phase of the cycle, backpressure is even more undesirable than in a four-stroke engine, as there is less time available for exhaust and the lack of pumping action from the piston to force the exhaust out of the cylinder.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] However, since the exhaust port necessarily remains open for a time after scavenging is completed, unburned mixture can follow the exhaust out of the cylinder, wasting fuel and increasing pollution.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] This can only be prevented if the pressure at the exhaust port is greater than that in the cylinder.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] Since the timing of this process is determined mainly by exhaust system geometry, which is extremely difficult to make variable, correct timing and therefore optimum engine efficiency can typically only be achieved over a small part of the engine's range of operating speed.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] Back-pressure is a useful diagnostic feature of problems with the chromatography column.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] Rapid chromatography is favoured by columns packed with very small particles, which create high back-pressures.
[src:boost-controller/backpressure] Column designers use "kinetic plots" to show the performance of a column at a constant back-pressure, usually selected as the maximum that a system's pump can reliably produce.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The balance shaft was invented and patented by British engineer Frederick W.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] It is most commonly used in inline-four and V6 engines used in automobiles and motorcycles.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The operating principle of a balance shaft system is that two shafts carrying identical eccentric weights rotate in opposite directions at twice the engine speed.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The phasing of the shafts is such that the centrifugal forces produced by the weights cancel the vertical second-order forces (at twice the engine RPM) produced by the engine.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The horizontal forces produced by the balance shafts are equal and opposite, and so cancel each other.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The balance shafts do not reduce the vibrations experienced by the crankshaft.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Numerous motorcycle engines— particularly parallel-twin engines— have employed balance shaft systems, for example the Yamaha TRX850 and Yamaha TDM850 engines have a 270° crankshaft with a balance shaft.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] An alternative approach, as used by the BMW GS parallel-twin, is to use a 'dummy' connecting rod which moves a hinged counterweight.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Balance shafts are often used in inline-four engines, to reduce the second-order vibration (a vertical force oscillating at twice the engine RPM) that is inherent in the design of a typical inline-four engine.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The amount of vibration also increases with engine displacement, resulting in balance shafts often being used in inline-four engines with displacements of 2.2 L (134 cu in) or more.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Both an increased stroke or bore cause an increased secondary vibration; a larger stroke increases the difference in acceleration and a larger bore increases the mass of the pistons.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] The Lanchester design of balance shaft systems was refined with the Mitsubishi Astron 80, an inline-four car engine introduced in 1975.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] This engine was the first to locate one balance shaft higher than the other, to counteract the second order rolling couple (i.e. about the crankshaft axis) due to the torque exerted by the inertia caused by increases and decreases in engine speed.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] In a flat-four engine, the forces are cancelled out by the pistons moving in opposite directions.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Therefore balance shafts are not needed in flat-four engines.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Balance shafts are also used in straight-five engines such as GM Vortec 3700.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] In a straight-six engine and flat-six engine, the rocking forces are naturally balanced out, therefore balance shafts are not required.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] V6 engines are inherently unbalanced, regardless of the V-angle.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Any inline engine with an odd number of cylinders has a primary imbalance, which causes an end-to-end rocking motion.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] As each cylinder bank in a V6 has three cylinders, each cylinder bank experiences this motion.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Balance shaft(s) are used on various V6 engines to reduce this rocking motion.
[src:boost-controller/balance-shaft] Examples are the Mercedes-Benz OM629 and Volvo B8444S engine.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] In turbocharged internal combustion engines, a **boost controller** is a device sometimes used to increase the boost pressure produced by the turbocharger.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] It achieves this by reducing the boost pressure seen by the wastegate.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] The purpose of a boost controller is to reduce the boost pressure seen by the wastegate's reference port, in order to trick the wastegate into allowing higher boost pressures than it was designed for.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Many boost controllers use a needle valve that is opened and closed by an electric solenoid.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] By varying the pulse width to the solenoid, the solenoid valve can be commanded to be open a certain percentage of the time.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] This effectively alters the flow rate of air pressure through the valve, changing the amount of air that is bled out instead of going to the wastegate's reference port.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Solenoids may require small diameter restrictors be installed in the air control lines to limit airflow and even out the on/off nature of their operation.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Two-port solenoid bleed systems with a PID controller tend to be common on factory turbocharged cars.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] An alternative design is to use a stepper motor.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] These designs allow fine control of airflow based on position and speed of the motor, but may have low total airflow capability.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Some systems use a solenoid in conjunction with a stepper motor, with the stepper motor allowing fine control and the solenoid coarse control.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Most modern designs are *electronic boost controllers* that use an electronic control unit to control the boost via a solenoid or stepper motor.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] The operating principle is the same as older *manual boost controllers*, which is to control the air pressure presented to the wastegate actuator.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Electronic controllers add greater flexibility in management of boost pressures, compared with the manual controllers.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] By keeping the wastegate in a closed position more often, a boost controller causes more of the exhaust gas to be routed through the turbocharger, thus reducing turbo lag and lowering the boost threshold.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Regardless of the effectiveness of the boost controller, wastegate actuator springs that are too soft can cause the wastegate to open before desired.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] This due to the exhaust gas backpressure pushing against the wastegate valve itself, causing the valve to open of the actuator at all.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Therefore, there is an upper limit to the effectiveness of a boost controller for a given spring stiffness in the wastegate actuator.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] To prevent excessive boost pressures in the event of a failure, the boost controller needs to be designed such that failure mode do not result in any pressure being bled off.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] For instance, a solenoid-type boost controller should direct all air to the wastegate when it is in the non-energized position (the common failure mode for a solenoid).
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Otherwise, the boost controller could get stuck in a position that lets no boost pressure reach the wastegate, causing boost to quickly rise out of control.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Also, the electronic systems, extra hoses, solenoids and control systems add cost and complexity.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Nonetheless, in recent times most automobile manufacturers use boost controllers on their turbocharged engines.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] In the past, boost pressures have been controlled by restricting or bleeding off some intake air before it reaches the intake manifold.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Designs which restrict the intake air can use a butterfly valve in the intake to restrict airflow as desired boost is approached.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Designs which bleed off the intake air functioned similar to a blowoff valve, but on a constant basis to maintain the desired boost pressure.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] These methods are rarely used in modern system due to the large sacrifices in efficiency, heat, and reliability.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Variable geometry turbocharger can be used to manage boost levels, negating the need for an external boost controller.
[src:boost-controller/boost-controller] Also, the wastegate itself has a similar function to a boost controller, in that it is used to manage the turbocharger's boost pressure.
